119
00:10:47.610 --> 00:10:52.309
Richard Vidutis: Him particularly, I can't think of anything special that he did.

120
00:10:52.840 --> 00:10:59.530
Richard Vidutis: he was, I don't think he was, he was focused on folklore.

121
00:10:59.930 --> 00:11:09.600
Richard Vidutis: stories… expressive… Events… But somehow, it was just that. I mean, we're not…

122
00:11:09.900 --> 00:11:16.879
Richard Vidutis: through the years, the stuff I've been doing is just very different. Still field work, still with people.

123
00:11:17.510 --> 00:11:22.230
Richard Vidutis: You have to really scrounge deep, looking for stuff.

124
00:11:22.730 --> 00:11:29.699
Richard Vidutis: He just kind of went in there with this mindset that he's gonna either find those stories or not.

125
00:11:29.900 --> 00:11:35.489
Richard Vidutis: That's why it's, labeled, is there a folk in the City? which is ridiculous. Of course there is.

126
00:11:36.120 --> 00:11:40.510
Richard Vidutis: He was just looking for those things, and he found what he was looking for.

127
00:11:40.890 --> 00:11:48.219
Richard Vidutis: But… That's it, then… That's not negative.

128
00:11:48.630 --> 00:11:54.389
Richard Vidutis: he, I think it was a really good folklore project when he carried that out.

129
00:11:55.360 --> 00:11:57.860
Richard Vidutis: carry it off. And,

130
00:11:59.330 --> 00:12:05.250
Richard Vidutis: beyond that, I don't know what to say. I mean, it wasn't anthropology, it wasn't anything else, it wasn't sociology.

131
00:12:05.940 --> 00:12:09.079
Richard Vidutis: So he did what he was after, and then he did,

132
00:12:10.040 --> 00:12:14.920
Richard Vidutis: With the, loggers, or they have with,

133
00:12:15.350 --> 00:12:20.929
Richard Vidutis: What did he do up in Michigan and in Maine? It was the same thing, more or less.

134
00:12:22.680 --> 00:12:24.539
Richard Vidutis: Just looking for the same stuff.

135
00:12:28.180 --> 00:12:40.070
Julie Stout: I want to next touch on the stories that reveal his character. I know you mentioned a few already, but are there any other specific anecdotes you can think of that illustrate what he was like to work with?

136
00:12:42.780 --> 00:12:50.040
Richard Vidutis: Just, again, when we were with them, we were careful to… do it correctly.

137
00:12:51.200 --> 00:12:56.849
Richard Vidutis: There was one little funny anecdote. It was at, I think a Croatian, maybe a Serbian.

138
00:12:57.790 --> 00:13:04.560
Richard Vidutis: I don't know what it was, some kind of a gathering, a lot of music and a lot of dancing, and he picked up the video.

139
00:13:05.060 --> 00:13:09.269
Richard Vidutis: And, he stuck the lens in his eye.

140
00:13:10.390 --> 00:13:19.409
Richard Vidutis: Like, if you take a camera and you stick the lens in your eye trying to take a picture of this. And I think he's on film somewhere doing that, something like that.

141
00:13:20.050 --> 00:13:26.290
Richard Vidutis: It just shows he had absolutely no technical understanding other than maybe the, you know, a cassette toy.

142
00:13:29.060 --> 00:13:41.889
Julie Stout: It must have been pretty interesting to see him in that context as well. Someone who's, like, a respected scholar, strict, as maybe you would say, and then he was kind of struggling with the technical aspects a bit.

143
00:13:42.770 --> 00:13:43.360
Richard Vidutis: Yep.

144
00:13:45.690 --> 00:13:47.469
Julie Stout: So my… oh, sorry.

145
00:13:47.960 --> 00:13:52.970
Richard Vidutis: I just want to add that I don't think he was very comfortable with with ethnics who…

146
00:13:53.100 --> 00:13:55.390
Richard Vidutis: Didn't speak English.

147
00:13:56.230 --> 00:14:02.719
Richard Vidutis: A lot of those didn't carry, you know? Like I said, I grew up speaking just Lithuanian with my parents.

148
00:14:03.150 --> 00:14:07.390
Richard Vidutis: A lot of people like that, like, I…

149
00:14:07.720 --> 00:14:13.010
Richard Vidutis: All my friends had either parents or grandparents who spoke the language.

150
00:14:13.970 --> 00:14:19.569
Richard Vidutis: And, that was the male language in many cases, it wasn't English.

151
00:14:19.890 --> 00:14:23.350
Richard Vidutis: So, I don't know how he felt about that. I mean…

152
00:14:23.760 --> 00:14:28.589
Richard Vidutis: That's why there isn't all that much. He writes about ethics, he has a whole chapter on it, but…

153
00:14:29.090 --> 00:14:36.469
Richard Vidutis: the language thing… He doesn't talk about that. Is there a folklore of steel? If there is.

154
00:14:36.590 --> 00:14:39.159
Richard Vidutis: He says there is some kind, I'm not sure what…

155
00:14:39.450 --> 00:14:42.330
Richard Vidutis: He's talking about, but there would have been…

156
00:14:43.180 --> 00:14:47.360
Richard Vidutis: And each respective ethnic group and their language.

157
00:14:47.490 --> 00:14:52.379
Richard Vidutis: That's for sure, and that's a whole different… Kettle of fish,

158
00:14:52.830 --> 00:14:54.990
Richard Vidutis: That he didn't approach so well.

159
00:14:55.140 --> 00:14:55.890
Richard Vidutis: Crystal.

160
00:14:56.070 --> 00:14:57.349
Richard Vidutis: For whatever reason.

161
00:15:01.520 --> 00:15:07.129
Julie Stout: I think… It's something interesting to think about, especially when you're going into

162
00:15:07.260 --> 00:15:11.030
Julie Stout: The fact that most of his students did speak a second language.

163
00:15:12.040 --> 00:15:22.639
Julie Stout: But he… did he not tell you to focus on people that spoke a different language and encourage you to speak that language with them? Or was it just capture these sorts of things?

164
00:15:22.640 --> 00:15:27.829
Richard Vidutis: I don't think he was concerned about language at all. He was always looking for expressive culture.

165
00:15:28.710 --> 00:15:29.400
Richard Vidutis: Wow.

166
00:15:30.280 --> 00:15:41.110
Richard Vidutis: Musicians, dancing, stories… Behaviors, opinions about…

167
00:15:41.980 --> 00:15:44.010
Richard Vidutis: Other people, that sort of stuff.

168
00:15:44.460 --> 00:15:46.310
Richard Vidutis: Typical folkloric stuff.

169
00:15:47.400 --> 00:15:53.329
Richard Vidutis: But… He's not… I don't think he spoke any other language, so…

170
00:15:54.470 --> 00:16:01.870
Richard Vidutis: It's… it's very difficult for somebody to come into a community like that, and… Try to understand it.

171
00:16:02.410 --> 00:16:07.690
Richard Vidutis: I mean, I've been up to Michigan, My fieldwork took…

172
00:16:07.990 --> 00:16:11.099
Richard Vidutis: Me a total of 13 months.

173
00:16:12.080 --> 00:16:13.230
Richard Vidutis: And I mean…

174
00:16:14.500 --> 00:16:20.100
Richard Vidutis: I've hung out with all kinds of what I call fins. They're American fins, but they're fins.

175
00:16:20.300 --> 00:16:23.500
Richard Vidutis: And, even to this day.

176
00:16:25.180 --> 00:16:28.960
Richard Vidutis: I'm not accepted, totally. You know, it's just the way it works.

177
00:16:30.100 --> 00:16:34.810
Richard Vidutis: And so there are things that I try to understand to find out.

178
00:16:36.370 --> 00:16:39.910
Richard Vidutis: And it's… Not gonna happen, so…

179
00:16:41.860 --> 00:16:46.560
Richard Vidutis: He should have leaned on, Atlanta in March.

180
00:16:46.870 --> 00:16:52.810
Richard Vidutis: And maybe hired somebody who spoke another language to get into those communities.

181
00:16:54.150 --> 00:17:01.310
Richard Vidutis: talk to them, interview them in their own languages. That would have been… wow, that would have been a totally different chapter.

182
00:17:04.599 --> 00:17:15.469
Julie Stout: I think it's something, like, an interesting perspective of what future fieldwork could look like in this community, is bringing in the language aspect into the fieldwork itself.

183
00:17:16.510 --> 00:17:17.089
Richard Vidutis: Yeah.

184
00:17:17.099 --> 00:17:17.559
Julie Stout: Yeah.

185
00:17:17.560 --> 00:17:19.249
Richard Vidutis: That would be really important.

186
00:17:19.250 --> 00:17:22.040
Julie Stout: It would kind of fill a gap, per se, maybe.

187
00:17:22.960 --> 00:17:24.130
Julie Stout: In this work.

188
00:17:24.420 --> 00:17:28.380
Julie Stout: So my last question regarding Dawson is about legacy.

